To implement the functionality you're asking for in your `PlayList` class—play next, play previous, and shuffle songs—you will need to track the current song index and also implement a method to shuffle your playlist. Here's one way you can modify the `PlayList` class to achieve this:

```javascript
class PlayList {
    constructor() {
        this.songs = [];
        this.currentIndex = 0;
    }

    playSong(id) {
        player.loadVideoById(id);
        this.currentIndex = this.songs.findIndex(song => song.videoId === id);
    }

    playNext() {
        if (this.currentIndex < this.songs.length - 1) {
            this.currentIndex++;
        } else {
            this.currentIndex = 0; // Loop back to start
        }
        this.playCurrentIndex();
    }

    playPrevious() {
        if (this.currentIndex > 0) {
            this.currentIndex--;
        } else {
            this.currentIndex = this.songs.length - 1; // Loop back to end
        }
        this.playCurrentIndex();
    }

    playCurrentIndex() {
        const song = this.songs[this.currentIndex];
        if (song) {
            this.playSong(song.videoId);
        }
    }

    shuffle() {
        for (let i = this.songs.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
            const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
            [this.songs[i], this.songs[j]] = [this.songs[j], this.songs[i]];
        }
        this.currentIndex = 0; // Reset index to play from the start of the shuffled list
    }

    loadPlaylist(type) {
        // Your existing code...
    }

    fetchJSON(url) {
        fetch(url)
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                this.songs.push(...data); // Assuming the JSON is an array of songs
                this.currentIndex = 0; // Reset the index to the start of the new playlist
            })
            .catch(error => {
                console.error('Error fetching JSON file:', error);
            });
    }
}

export default PlayList;
```

In this updated class:

- The `playNext` and `playPrevious` functions update `this.currentIndex` and ensure that it wraps around the playlist, i.e., it loops to the beginning or the end when it reaches the last or the first song, respectively.

- The `playCurrentIndex` function plays the song at the `currentIndex`.

- The `shuffle` function uses the modern version of the Fisher-Yates algorithm to shuffle the array of songs randomly.

- The `fetchJSON` now uses the spread operator when pushing new songs assuming that the incoming data from the JSON file is an array.

Now, to use these methods with your YouTube player, when the user clicks the next, previous, or shuffle buttons, you will tie those to respective methods in your `PlayList` instance. Here is how you would might attach event listeners to these buttons:

```javascript
const playlist = new PlayList();

document.getElementById('nextButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
