My friend says my code will be a lot cleaner if I turn these objects into a class. Is he right? I feel like it'll simply cause a lot of uneeded boilerplate code since classes are used for something that requires the use of several instances of an object

Your friend has a point that classes can provide a cleaner structure, especially when it comes to inheritance and method organization. They also offer syntax that many developers find more readable and familiar, particularly for those coming from other object-oriented languages. However, whether it is beneficial to use a class in this specific case depends on several factors:

1. **Instances**: If you only ever intend to create a single instance of each module, as it seems from your current code, the necessity of using classes is less compelling. The prototypal model you're using now is perfectly valid in JavaScript and can be more flexible in some cases.

2. **Complexity**: If the modules become more complex or you find yourself repeating code across multiple modules, classes might help consolidate and simplify through inheritance, but that might not be necessary in this case.

3. **Maintenance**: As your codebase grows, classes can help make your code more maintainable. This could make it easier for other developers to understand and contribute to your project, especially if they are more familiar with class-based structures.

4. **Features**: JavaScript classes provide features like constructor functions, instance methods, getters and setters, and static methods. If you need these features, a class structure could be beneficial.

5. **Boilerplate**: While using classes might introduce some boilerplate code, it often leads to a more organized and systematic approach, which can outweigh the initial verbosity.

Here is what a class-based version of one of your modules could look like:

```javascript
class Module {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
        this.enabled = false;
    }

    toggle() {
        this.enabled = !this.enabled;
        sendPackets.systemChat('[System]', `Toggled ${this.name}: ${this.enabled ? 'ON' : 'OFF'}`);
        if (this.onToggle) {
            this.onToggle();
        }
    }

    set(options) {
        Object.assign(this, options);
        console.log(options);
    }
}

class ChatSpamModule extends Module {
    constructor() {
        super('Chat Spam');
        this.intervalId = null;
        this.msg = 'Skill Issue';
        this.delay = 1000;
    }

    onToggle() {
        if (this.enabled) {
            this.intervalId = setInterval(() => sendPackets.chat(this.msg), this.delay);
        } else {
            clearInterval(this.intervalId);
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
const spamChat = new ChatSpamModule();
```

This class structure provides a more traditional inheritance model, which could be advantageous if you are planning on further scaling your system or creating multiple instances of certain types of modules.

Ultimately, whether sticking with a prototypal pattern or switching to classes is the better approach will depend on your specific needs, the scale of your project, personal preference, and coding style. Both have their uses, and neither is inherently superior for all cases.

When your friend suggests making major objects into classes, they are advocating for an approach that focuses on the use of classes for the key components of your application that may benefit from the structure and formalism that classes provide in JavaScript. Here’s why this could be beneficial:

1. **Encapsulation**: Classes help encapsulate behavior with associated data. This can lead to more intuitive and self-contained code. Encapsulation can also make it easier to understand each part of the system in isolation.

2. **Inheritance**: If you have common functionality that is shared across multiple objects, you can define a base class with this shared functionality, and then have other classes inherit from it. This promotes code reuse and can reduce duplication.

3. **Readability**: While readability can be subjective, many developers find class-based code easier to understand, especially if they are familiar with object-oriented programming from other languages.

4. **Maintenance**: As systems grow, having classes can make code more maintainable. Clear inheritance hierarchies and encapsulation can make it easier to modify one part of the system without inadvertently affecting other parts.

5. **Constructor Method**: Classes provide a constructor method for creating and initializing objects created with a class. This can be more clear than using an `Object.create()` approach with a factory function.

