When using `Object.create` to define properties with the second argument (the property descriptor), you don't have to set `writable: true` unless you want the property to be able to be changed after the object is created. Here's what happens with and without `writable: true`:

With `writable: true`:
- You can assign new values to the property after the object is created.
- You're indicating that the property is allowed to be overwritten.

Without `writable` specified or with `writable: false` set explicitly:
- The property will be read-only.
- You'll get a TypeError if you try to assign a new value to the property in strict mode (this is ignored otherwise, but the assignment will fail).

If you omit `writable` entirely in the property descriptor, its default value is `false`. So, if you plan to change the properties later (e.g., `msg` or `delay`), you should explicitly set `writable: true`.

